accomodations_needed: I asked for a raise because I had to get new medication that my insurance didn't cover. They gave me a fraction of that raise and I just had to cut corners and figure it out. I only told my main supervisor I was tempted to quit over it, considering they get more from me than I get from them. Even with the salary. And I shouldn't be thought of as less than simply because I'm a person with disabilities and not a lawyer.  Funny enough, I'm the first person with disabilities that they hired, which says a lot about an organization. It took a full year of begging to get grab bars in the bathroom. I didn't even realize I had to beg for them. I shouldn't have to ask for it. And if I do, I shouldn't be made to feel bad that I did ask.

trans_challenges_oth: I mostly drive, but if  I did not have a car, the public transit options here would not be sufficient for getting to work,

Newly blind by 5 years - never rode bus by myself, have to use public transportation  in city - uses fixed route, advisory board doesn't listen to ideas and suggestions - accountability issues, rules only apply to passengers (drivers don't have accountability)  pickup window 12-1; drivers get routes assigned, not making decisions(management); Problems get stuck on riders, and   issues in Buffalo similar to NYC b/c they're used to doing things the same way (20th century); went to computer system for booking trips, shuffles trips every 20 minutes in case the driver is late. Set the system up w/out correct parameters. Snow storm in one neighborhood, buses run late/have issues, and buses are sent too far (north to south) but it takes too long. When drivers are running late and explain, they get ostracized.   Thankful for service, but it could be improved and made better. Management doesn't listen. Challenged to ride the service for a week, said they can't take paratransit. 3/4 mile rule - State legislature is trying to expand it. Affected by 3/4 mile rule. Monday - Friday, transportation is decent. Saturday and Sunday, since I live past 3/4 mile boundary, can't get paratransit (homebound). Dispatcher gave information of where to go to get picked up. Rules have room to wiggle, may be enforced differently. 5 minute pick up rule. Sometimes they'll wait up to 25 minutes for someone, need equal application of the rules.   People overhelp, don't know how to help. If you don't guide them to what you need, like telling people how to guide a nonsighted person (be in front, use shoulder, for example). Trying to get information is vague, transferring always needs assistance and direction. Fixed route drivers are very helpful, some even insisted on assisting in crossing street. When drivers do a good job, I give commendations. Bus station and train station layouts are not friendly for people with low vision or physical disabilities.  Uber and Lyft have program called """"Go Go Grandparent"""" - concierge service to book uber or lyft.  Air travel is good, have never had issue.
